{"title_page": "Red (King Crimson album)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Red\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[King Crimson]]\n| cover        = Red, King Crimson.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 6 October 1974\n| recorded     = 30 June \u2013 August 1974\n| venue        = [[Providence Performing Arts Center|Palace Theater]], [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence, RI]]\n| studio       = [[Olympic Studios|Olympic]], London\n| genre        = [[Progressive rock]], [[Hard rock]]\n| length       = 39:54\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| producer     = King Crimson\n| prev_title   = [[Starless and Bible Black]]\n| prev_year    = 1974\n| next_title   = [[USA (King Crimson album)|USA]]\n| next_year    = 1975\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[King Crimson]] studio\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Starless and Bible Black]]\n | prev_year  = 1974\n | title      = Red\n | year       = 1974\n | next_title = [[Discipline (King Crimson album)|Discipline]]\n | next_year  = 1981}}\n}}\n\n'''''Red''''' is the seventh studio album by English [[progressive rock]] group [[King Crimson]]. It was released on 6 October 1974 through [[Island Records]] in the United Kingdom and [[Atlantic Records]] in North America. It was their last studio recording of the 1970s and the last before lead member [[Robert Fripp]] temporarily disbanded the group. Though their lowest-charting album at the time, spending only one week in the UK charts, ''Red'' has received significant critical acclaim.\n\n== Writing and recording ==\n\nMuch of the material on ''Red'' has origins in improvisation. Motifs that would eventually be used for \"Fallen Angel\" were first played by Robert Fripp in 1972, as part of improvs performed with the quintet lineup that would record ''Larks' Tongues In Aspic''. These improvisations are documented as \"Fallen Angel\" and \"Fallen Angel Hullabaloo\" in the ''[[Larks' Tongues in Aspic: The Complete Recordings]]'' box set, as well as standalone releases of their respective concerts. The distinctive introduction to \"One More Red Nightmare\" was also deployed by [[John Wetton]] and Robert Fripp in various improvs throughout 1974, which can be heard in the ''[[Starless (box set)]]'' and ''[[The Road to Red]]'' box sets. One notable performance is titled \"The Golden Walnut\". Lastly, \"Providence\" itself was an improv, taken from the group's show on 30 June in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. It has been included in its uncut form as part of various live sets, such as ''[[The Great Deceiver (King Crimson album)|The Great Deceiver]]'', as well as the 40th Anniversary Edition of ''Red'' itself.\n\n\"Red\" was composed solely by Robert Fripp. In an analysis of the piece by [[Andrew Keeling]], he describes \"Red\" as \"an instrumental piece scored for electric guitar (multi-tracked X3), bass guitar and drums,\" as well as \"one of the more muscular pieces of Robert Fripp's, in particular the deployment of open strings and heavily attacked and syncopated bass and drums.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keeling|first1=Andrew|authorlink1=Andrew Keeling|title=King Crimson: Red \u2013 An Analysis by Andrew Keeling|url=http://www.songsouponsea.com/Keeling/Keeling-Red.html|website=Song Soup on Sea|publisher=Peter Sinfield|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref> In an online diary from 2012, Robert Fripp speaks about the development of \"Red\": \"A motif; moved from [the missing piece] \"Blue\" to \"Red\": the opening and closing theme of \"Red\" itself. The driving, relentless figure that follows it, and the middle figure played by the basses, weren't enough for a complete piece.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dgmlive.com/diaries/Robert%20Fripp/dgm-hq-while-in-the-210916 |title=DGM HQ |last=Fripp |first=Robert |publisher=Discipline Global Mobile |date=June 12, 2012 |website=DGM Live |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> Speaking about it in the book accompanying the ''[[Larks' Tongues in Aspic: The Complete Recordings]]'' box set, he says, \"After we had just recorded the track \"Red\" in [[Olympic Studios|[Olympic Studios]]] ... we played it back and [[Bill Bruford|Bill]] said, 'I don't get it, but if you tell me it's good, I trust you.' ... I said, 'We don't have to use it.' John was in no doubt: 'We'll use it.'\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Singleton |first=David |authorlink=David Singleton |date=2012 |title=Larks' Tongues in Aspic: The Complete Recordings |chapter=Robert Fripp interviwed by David Singleton |pages=10 }}</ref> In retrospect, \"Red\" has been considered an influence on [[avant-garde metal]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AVQbF9lTBwgC&pg=PA337|title=The Mojo Collection: 4th Edition|date=2007|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=9781847676436|page=337}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' ranked \"Red\" as the twentieth best progressive rock song of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/141547-best-25-rock-songs-of-all-time-2496025727.html?rebelltpage=2|title=The 25 Best Progressive Rock Songs of All Time|last=Murphy|first=Sean|date=22 May 2011|website=[[PopMatters]]|access-date=4 April 2019}}</ref> An unused rhythmical variation of the song's middle section would see light more than two decades later, when it was included in 1995's ''[[Thrak]]'' album as the middle section of the instrumental ''Vrooom Vrooom'' track (albeit with [[Tony Levin]]\u2019s bass and [[Trey Gunn]]\u2019s [[Chapman Stick]] in place of Wetton).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dgmlive.com/in-depth/the-double-trio-robert-fripp|title=The Double Trio - Robert Fripp|first=|last=|date=7 November 2016|website=DGM Live}}</ref>\n\n\"Starless\" was originally written by Wetton, with the intent of it being the title track for ''[[Starless and Bible Black]]''. At the time, the piece consisted only of the vocal section of the song, and Wetton claims that it got a \"cold reception\" from both Robert Fripp and Bill Bruford. Later, an introductory theme was written by Robert Fripp and performed on violin by [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]], and two additional sections were added after the vocal, one being contributed by Bruford.<ref name=BoffomuInt>{{cite web |last1=Curtiss |first1=Ron |last2=Weiner |first2=Aaron |title=John Wetton (King Crimson, U.K., Asia): The Complete Boffomundo Interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-hcovFGVW44 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=3 March 2019 |date=June 3, 2016}} Event occurs at 5:15\u20137:01.</ref> The final section reprises various themes from earlier in the song, and it also re-uses a bass part which was originally written for the song \"Fracture\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dgmlive.com/tour-dates/295 |title=University of Texas Arlington |last=Smith |first=Sid |publisher=Discipline Global Mobile |website=DGM Live |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> This early arrangement of \"Fracture\" can be heard on discs 1 and 25 of the ''[[Starless (box set)|Starless]]'' box set, as well as the standalone releases of their respective concerts. The lyrics went through several iterations, with one early verse later included by Wetton in \"Caesar's Palace Blues,\" a song he would perform with [[U.K. (band)|U.K.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bakerloo2.forumchitchat.com/post/show_single_post?pid=1268162733&postcount=2|title=John Wetton, Official John Wetton Website Guestbook|website=Bakerloo2.forumchitchat.com|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref> Since the title \"Starless and Bible Black\" was already used for an improvisation on the group's previous album, the song's title was shortened to \"Starless\".<ref name=BoffomuInt/> On ''Red'', \"Starless\" is credited to the quartet, as well as lyricist [[Richard Palmer-James]].\n\nThe lyrics to the three songs on the album were not originally included as part of the packaging for the album, unlike all previous Crimson studio albums, which always had lyrics printed either on the inside of the gatefold covers, or on the custom innersleeves. This led to some occasional confusion amongst listeners about precisely what was being sung, particularly on the song \"One More Red Nightmare.\" The first printing of the lyrics would occur 26 years after the album's initial release, on the 2000 '30th Anniversary Edition' release.\n\nNear the conclusion of King Crimson's 1974 [[North America]]n tour, the decision was made to kick Cross out of the band. [[E.G. Records|EG]], the band's management, urged Fripp not to tell Cross until after the final date of the tour, but he would not be able to anyway; he would not return from the [[United States]] until after Cross would return to [[Europe]]. Fripp reached an agreement with EG that they would tell Cross, \"on proviso that [he] is told that I objected to not telling him personally.\" Despite reaching this agreement, Cross would not be told about the decision for him to leave the band until the day before the recording of ''Red'' began.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fripp |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Fripp |date=2013 |title=The Road To Red |chapter=Robert Fripp Diaries |pages=32 }}</ref> In his stead, the band brought back several contributors to past albums: [[Robin Miller (musician)|Robin Miller]] on [[oboe]], [[Marc Charig]] on [[cornet]], [[Ian McDonald (musician)|Ian McDonald]] and [[Mel Collins]] on [[saxophone]], as well as an uncredited [[cello|cellist]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dgmlive.com/in-depth/red-the-long-view|title=Red \u2013 The Long View|date=2016-11-03|work=DGM Live|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''Red'' sees King Crimson follow in the direction established by their previous two albums, ''[[Larks' Tongues in Aspic]]'' and ''Starless and Bible Black'', but in contrast to those albums, ''Red'' features more layered production with several [[guitar]] [[overdubs]] on certain tracks, as well as the return of earlier instrumentation such as saxophone. ''Red'' having a heavier tone was largely due to the [[rhythm section]] of John Wetton and Bill Bruford, which Fripp has referred to as \"the flying brick wall\". During the recording of the album, Fripp took a \"backseat\" when making large decisions.<ref name=\"mountains come out\">{{cite book |last=Romano |first1=Will |title=Mountains Come Out of the Sky: The Illustrated History of Prog Rock |publisher=Backbeat Books |date=2010 |isbn=978-0879309916 |quote=\"At the time we were recording [Red], Robert Fripp said he wanted to take a backseat, because he wasn't sure where this [band] was going\", Wetton said. }}</ref> He had decided to take \"a year's sabbatical ... at [[John G. Bennett#International Academy for Continuous Education|Bennett's Institute]],\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dgmlive.com/diaries/Robert%20Fripp/idea-my-years-sabbatical-could-210916 |title=Idea my years sabbatical |last=Fripp |first=Robert |publisher=Discipline Global Mobile |date=July 8, 1974 |website=DGM Live |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> and offered the idea of McDonald rejoining the band in his absence to EG. When this idea was met with disinterest, Fripp abruptly disbanded King Crimson on 24 September 1974, and ''Red'' was released a month later.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Sid |authorlink=Sid Smith (writer) |date=2013 |title=The Road To Red |chapter=Nowhere to go but everywhere... |pages=14 }}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r10912 |title=Red \u2013 King Crimson &#124; AllMusic |first=B. |last=Eder |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2Score = A\u2013<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: K|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=K&bk=70|accessdate=February 28, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|8|10}}<ref name=\"classic\" >{{cite magazine |title=King Crimson \u2013 Reissues |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |date=November 2009 |last=Milas |first=Alexander  |issue=138 |page=95}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev4Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal| last= Barnes| first= Mike|date=November 2009| title= Royal Flush| journal     = Mojo| issue = 192| page= 106| publisher= [[Bauer Media Group]]| location= London| issn= 1351-0193| ref= harv}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev5Score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite journal|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=September 10, 2017|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/king-crimson-red/|title=King Crimson: Red|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=September 10, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\nReleased in October 1974, ''Red'' spent only one week on the British charts, at No. 45, whereas all the band's previous studio albums had reached the Top 30. In the United States, it reached No. 66 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. However, it remained a popular album with fans and critics.\n\nRetrospective reviews were resoundingly positive. In theirs, [[AllMusic]] declared ''Red'' to be weaker than its two predecessors, but nonetheless a superlative work: \"few intact groups could have gotten an album as good as ''Red'' together. The fact that it was put together by a band in its death throes makes it all the more impressive an achievement.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] also applauded the album, having been generally critical of the group's past work, calling it \"Grand, powerful, grating, and surprisingly lyrical\" and commenting that \"this does for classical-rock fusion what [[John McLaughlin (musician)|John McLaughlin]]'s ''[[Devotion (John McLaughlin album)|Devotion]]'' did for jazz-rock fusion.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/> ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' reviewer considered ''Red'' \"a walk down a lightless corridor and an unhappy and ferocious counterbalance to the frolics of King Crimson's beginnings\", and described it as \"dark, brooding and laden with heavily distorted sections and a decidedly melancholic vibe\".<ref name=\"classic\"/>\n\nLike most of King Crimson's catalogue, ''Red'' has been re-released numerous times since its release. First issued on CD in 1986, it has also been released as part of the Definitive Edition and 30th Anniversary Edition series. In 2009, ''Red'' was chosen, alongside ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]'' and ''[[Lizard (album)|Lizard]]'', to launch the 40th Anniversary Edition series. As part of this series, each album is presented in a CD/DVD-A package, with new [[stereo]] and [[surround|5.1 surround]] mixes. Unlike most others in series, however, ''Red'' launched with no new stereo mix. In 2013, Steven Wilson and Robert Fripp produced a stereo remix for ''[[The Road To Red]]'', and this mix was issued separately as part of a 2CD package.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2001, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] named ''Red'' as one of the \"50 Heaviest Albums of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage2.html#50+Heaviest|title=Rocklist.net...Q Magazine Lists|website=Rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref> and [[Kurt Cobain]] had reportedly cited the album as a major influence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elephant-talk.com/wiki/Interview_with_Robert_Fripp_in_Rock_and_Folk|title=Interview with Robert Fripp in Rock and Folk \u2013 ETWiki|website=Elephant-talk.com|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elephant-talk.com/wiki/Interview_with_Bill_Bruford_in_Percussioni_(in_Italian)|title=Interview with Bill Bruford in Percussioni (in Italian) \u2013 ETWiki|website=Elephant-talk.com|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref> Musicologists Eric Tamm and Edward Macan both consider ''Red'', and particularly the track \"[[Starless]]\", to be the highlight of King Crimson's recorded output.\n\nThe title track was ranked number 87 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of \"The 100 Greatest Guitar Songs\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080530224813/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/20947527/page/36 ''Rolling Stone'' \u2013 The 100 Greatest Guitar Songs of All Time]. Retrieved 2011-01-24. \"\u2018I'm not a blues guitarist\u2019, Robert Fripp said in 1995, 'but I think I've met the spirit of the blues several times.' This is one of them: blunt-instrument funk in which Fripp, leading a power-trio Crimson, jars the mathematical cadence of his riffing with a wrecking-ball swing and rude pig-squeal harmonics.\"</ref> [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] ranked ''Red'' number 72 in its \"Top 100 Albums of the 1970s\" list, stating that \"For a band that was very obviously about to splinter, King Crimson's music sounds remarkably of a single mind. On ''Red'', they achieved a remarkable balance between bone-crushing brutality and cerebral complexity.\"<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/ ''Pitchfork'' \u2013 Top 100 Albums of the 1970s]. Retrieved 2016-03-18.</ref>\n\nThe title track was covered by Canadian rock band [[Glueleg]] in their 1994 debut ''Heroic Doses'', with this version featuring saxophone and trumpet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Glueleg-Heroic-Doses/release/1810967|title=Glueleg - Heroic Doses|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\n\"Starless\" is played over the opening titles of the 2018 horror film ''[[Mandy (2018 film)|Mandy]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = Red\n| writer1 = [[Robert Fripp]]\n| length1 = 6:20\n| title2 = [[Fallen Angel (King Crimson song)|Fallen Angel]]\n| writer2 = Fripp, [[John Wetton]], [[Richard Palmer-James]]\n| length2 = 6:00\n| title3 = [[One More Red Nightmare]]\n| writer3 = Fripp, Wetton\n| length3 = 7:07\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title4 = Providence\n| writer4 = [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]], Fripp, Wetton, [[Bill Bruford]]\n| length4 = 8:08\n| title5 = [[Starless]]\n| writer5 = Cross, Fripp, Wetton, Bruford, Palmer-James\n| length5 = 12:18\n}}\n\n=== 2009 40th Anniversary edition ===\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc one \u2013 CD \u2013 Original Album \u2013 bonus tracks\n| collapsed = yes\n| title1 = Red\n| writer1 = [[Robert Fripp]]\n| length1 = 6:20\n| note1  = Original Album \n| title2 = [[Fallen Angel (King Crimson song)|Fallen Angel]]\n| writer2 = Fripp, [[John Wetton]], [[Richard Palmer-James]]\n| length2 = 6:00\n| note2  = Original Album \n| title3 = [[One More Red Nightmare]]\n| writer3 = Fripp, Wetton\n| length3 = 7:07\n| note3  = Original Album \n| title4 = Providence\n| writer4 = [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]], Fripp, Wetton, [[Bill Bruford]]\n| length4 = 8:08\n| note4  = Original Album \n| title5 = [[Starless]]\n| writer5 = Cross, Fripp, Wetton, Bruford, Palmer-James\n| length5 = 12:18\n| note5  = Original Album\n| title6 = Red\n| writer6 = Fripp\n| length6 = 6:27\n| note6  = Bonus Tracks \u2013 Pre-overdub trio version\n| title7 = Fallen Angel\n| writer7 = Fripp, Wetton\n| length7 = 6:26\n| note7  = Bonus Tracks \u2013 Pre-overdub trio version instrumental\n| title8 = Providence\n| writer8 = Cross, Fripp, Wetton, Bruford\n| length8 = 10:09\n| note8  = Bonus Tracks \u2013 Unedited live version taken from ''[[The Great Deceiver (King Crimson album)|The Great Deceiver]]''\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Disc two \u2013 DVD-A (various mixes, bonuses and video content)\n| collapsed = yes\n| title1 = Red\n| writer1 = [[Robert Fripp]]\n| length1 = 6:20\n| note1  = Original Album [MLP Lossless Stereo (24/96) / PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48)]\n| t