 Stereo 2.0 (24/48) - 12\" Dance mix\n\n| title55     = Discipline\n| writer55    = \n| length55    = 5:13\n| note55      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48) - Instrumental\n| title56     = Thela Hun Ginjeet\n| writer56    = \n| length56    = 6:26\n| note56      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48)\n| title57     = Matte Kudasai\n| writer57    = \n| length57    = 3:47\n| note57      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48) - {{Nihongo2|\u5f85\u3063\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044}}, Please Wait\n| title58     = Elephant Talk\n| writer58    = \n| length58    = 4:43\n| note58      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48)\n| title59     = The Sheltering Sky\n| writer59    = \n| length59    = 8:22\n| note59      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48) - Instrumental\n| title60     = Frame by Frame\n| writer60    = \n| length60    = 5:09\n| note60      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48)\n| title61     = Indiscipline\n| writer61    = \n| length61    = 4:33\n| note61      = Album Rough Mixes - PCM Stereo 2.0 (24/48)\n\n| title62     = Elephant Talk\n| writer62    = \n| length62    = 4:47\n| note62      = Video Content - Selections From The Old Grey Whistle Test - Recorded live at [[The Venue (Victoria Street, London)|The Venue]], [[London]], [[England]], 9 October 1981\n| title63     = Frame by Frame\n| writer63    = \n| length63    = 4:44\n| note63      = Video Content - Selections From The Old Grey Whistle Test - Recorded at the [[BBC]], 15 March 1982, introduced by [[Annie Nightingale]]\n| title64     = Indiscipline\n| writer64    = \n| length64    = 6:52\n| note64      = Video Content - Selections From The Old Grey Whistle Test - Recorded at the BBC, 15 March 1982, introduced by Annie Nightingale\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*King Crimson \u2013 [[Record producer|production]]\n*[[Adrian Belew]] \u2013 [[electric guitar]], [[guitar synthesizer]], [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]] (1-5), voice loops (2, 6)\n*[[Robert Fripp]] \u2013 electric guitar, guitar synthesizer, devices ([[Frippertronics]])\n*[[Tony Levin]] \u2013 [[Chapman Stick]] (1-2, 4, 6-7), [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] (2, 5), [[Bass guitar|bass]] (3, 5)\n*[[Bill Bruford]] \u2013 [[drums]] (1-5, 7), [[slit drum]] (6-7)\n\n'''Technical'''\n*[[Rhett Davies]] \u2013 production\n*Nigel Mills \u2013 assistant [[Audio engineer|engineer]]\n*Graham Davies \u2013 gear\n*[[Peter Saville (graphic designer)|Peter Saville]] \u2013 graphic design\n*John Kyrk \u2013 [[knot]]work<ref>{{cite web|url=http://et.stok.ca/articles/562-8.html|title=\"Discipline\" Celtic Knotwork|date=22 December 1998|website=et.stok.ca|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref> (uncredited; 1981, 1986 and 1989 issues only)\n*Steve Ball \u2013 knotwork (2001 issue onwards)\n*Paddy Spinks \u2013 [[Talent manager#Music managers|strategic management]]\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1981)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Album chart | Billboard200 | 45 | artist = King Crimson  | accessdate = 14 November 2017 | refname = \"US Billboard 200\"}}\n|-\n{{Album chart | UK | 41 | artist = King Crimson | date = 1981-10-10 | accessdate = 14 November 2017 | refname = \"UK chart\"}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{Discogs master|577|Discipline}}\n*[http://www.elephant-talk.com/wiki/Discipline Wiki with song lyrics] at fan-site  Elephant Talk (inspired by ''Discipline'''s \"[[Elephant Talk]]\")\n\n{{King Crimson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Discipline (King Crimson Album)}}\n[[Category:1981 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rhett Davies]]\n[[Category:King Crimson albums]]\n[[Category:E.G. Records albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n[[Category:New wave albums by English artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Discipline\n| type         = Studio\n| artist       = [[King Crimson]]\n| cover        = Discipline_-_Original_Vinyl_Cover.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 22 September 1981\n| recorded     = May \u2013 June 1981\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Sarm West Studios|Basing Street Studios]], [[Notting Hill]], London, England\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Progressive rock]]<ref name=\"cr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/king-crimson-a-guide-to-their-best-albums|title=King Crimson: a guide to their best albums|last=Dome|first=Malcolm|date=29 January 2019|website=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]]|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[post-progressive]]<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Bruford|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Bruford|title=Bill Bruford: The Autobiography : Yes, King Crimson, Earthworks, and More|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z_7VsmxN0sYC&pg=PA125|year=2009|publisher=Jawbone Press|isbn=978-1-906002-23-7}}</ref>\n*[[new wave music|new wave]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/beat-mw0000194479 |title=''Beat'' \u2013 King Crimson |last=Prato |first=Greg |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref>\n*[[dance-rock]]<ref name=\"TP\" />\n*[[art rock]]<ref name=\"cr\" />}}\n| length       = 38:15\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[E.G. Records|E.G.]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n}}\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* King Crimson\n* [[Rhett Davies]]\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[USA (album)|USA]]\n| prev_year    = 1975\n| next_title   = [[Beat (King Crimson album)|Beat]]\n| next_year    = 1982\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[King Crimson]] studio\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Red (King Crimson album)|Red]]\n | prev_year  = 1974\n | title      = Discipline\n | year       = 1981\n | next_title = [[Beat (King Crimson album)|Beat]]\n | next_year  = 1982\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Discipline\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Matte Kudasai]]\" / \"[[Elephant Talk]]\n | single1date = September 1981\n | single2     = [[Thela Hun Ginjeet]]\n | single2date = September 1981\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Discipline''''' is the eighth studio album by English [[progressive rock]] band [[King Crimson]], released on September 22, 1981 by [[E.G. Records]] in the United Kingdom and by [[Warner Bros. Records]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://movingtheriver.com/2016/10/10/king-crimsons-discipline-35-years-old-today/ |title=King Crimson's Discipline: 35 Years Old Today |last=Phillips |first=Matt |date=2016-10-10 |website=movingtheriver.com |access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref> This album was King Crimson's first album following a seven-year hiatus. Only founder [[Robert Fripp]] and later addition [[Bill Bruford]] remained from previous incarnations. The rest of the band were American musicians [[Adrian Belew]] (guitar, lead vocals) and [[Tony Levin]] (bass guitar, [[Chapman Stick]], backing vocals). The album resulted in a more updated 1980s [[New wave music|new wave]]-oriented sound.\n\n== Background and composition ==\n\"[[Matte Kudasai]]\" ({{lang-ja|\u5f85\u3063\u3066\u4e0b\u3055\u3044}}) literally means \"please wait\". The original release of ''Discipline'' featured only one version of \"Matte Kudasai\", with a guitar part by [[Robert Fripp]] that was removed from the track on a subsequent release of the album. The latest versions of the album to be released contains both versions of the song \u2013 track 3, \"Matte Kudasai\", without Robert Fripp's original guitar part; and track 8, \"Matte Kudasai (alternative version)\", with the guitar part included. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dgmlive.com/diaries/Robert%20Fripp/chop-em-out-mastering-olympia-210916 |title=Chop Em Out Mastering Olympia |last=Fripp |first=Robert |date=2001-01-09 |website=Robert Fripp's Diary |publisher=DGM Live |access-date=2017-07-29 |quote= We are listening to the alternative version of \"Matte\" with RF on sustained guitar lines and solo. This is the version included on the original 1981 \"Discipline\" release, and was later replaced by the original pre-overdub minimalist mix on releases after 1989. In Island studios, recording and mixing of the album completed, Adrian & I agreed that something more was needed for \"Matte\". He left it to me to come up with something, flew home, but when he heard my contribution wasn't convinced. I agree. This new re-release gives us the opportunity to include both versions, in accordance with a suggestion made a while ago on the Guestbook. }} </ref>\n\nThe lyrics of \"[[Indiscipline]]\" were based on a letter written to [[Adrian Belew]] by his then-wife Margaret, concerning a painting that she had made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elephant-talk.com/wiki/Interview_with_King_Crimson_in_Trouser_Press|title=Interview with King Crimson in Trouser Press|last=Arthur|first=Stephen|date=8 February 1995|website=ET Wiki|publisher=[[Trouser Press]]|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Thela Hun Ginjeet]]\" is an [[anagram]] of \"heat in the jungle\". When it was first performed live, some of its lyrics were improvised around an illicit recording made by Robert Fripp of his neighbours having a vicious argument when he was living in New York; this recording is featured on the track \"NY3\" on Fripp's solo album ''[[Exposure (Robert Fripp album)|Exposure]]''.{{citation needed|reason=The claim regarding use of the New York tape is most likely false. The live in Bath 1981 recording by the band Discipline, which was the song's live premier, gives evidence of Belew singing \"My House, Your House\", but no evidence of the NY3 recording at all|date=March 2015}} While the track was being recorded for the ''Discipline'' album, Adrian Belew, walking around [[Notting Hill Gate]] in [[London]] with a [[tape recorder]] looking for inspiration, was harassed first by a gang and then by the police. On returning to the studio, he gave a distraught account to his bandmates of what had just happened to him. This account was recorded by Fripp, without Belew's knowledge, as well <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elephant-blog.blogspot.com/2007/04/anecdote-808.html|title=elephant blog: Anecdote # 808|last=Belew|first=Adrian|authorlink=Adrian Belew|date=2007-04-03|website=elephant blog|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref> and is featured on the ''Discipline'' version of the track (as well as almost all live versions), in place of those earlier lyrics that were based on Fripp's New York recording.\n\n\"The Sheltering Sky\" is named after and partially inspired by [[The Sheltering Sky|the 1949 novel of the same name]] by [[Paul Bowles]]. Bowles is often associated with the [[Beat generation]], which would be an inspiration for King Crimson's subsequent studio album ''[[Beat (King Crimson album)|Beat]]''.\n\n[[File:\"Possible Productions knotwork\" by Steve Ball.png|left|thumb|Later versions of ''Discipline'' featured this design by Steve Ball.]]\n\nLive versions of \"Elephant Talk\", \"Indiscipline\", and \"Thela Hun Ginjeet\" included partial vocal improvisation during spoken-word parts. One such example can be found in the 13 August 1982 performance, which, as of 12 August 2014, was still available for download in both [[MP3]] and [[FLAC]] formats from [[Discipline Global Mobile|DGM]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe back cover features the statement, \"Discipline is never an end in itself, only a means to an end\". The original front cover features a variation on a copyrighted [[Celtic knot]] design by [[George Bain (artist)|George Bain]].<ref name=georgebain>{{cite book |first=George|last=Bain|authorlink=George Bain (artist)|title=Celtic art: The methods of construction |year=1951 |publisher=Constable Press|location=London |isbn=|ref=harv}}<br/>{{cite book |first=George |last=Bain |title=Celtic Art: The Methods of Construction |year=1973 |publisher=Dover Publications, Inc |location= |isbn=0-486-22923-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/methodsofconstru00bain }}</ref> As it was found to be used without Bain's permission, it was replaced on later releases by a knotwork designed by Steve Ball on commission from Robert Fripp.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.steveball.com/words/archive/2001/2001-10-01.htm#saturday|first=Steve|last=Ball|chapter=Saturday September 29|title=Steve&nbsp;Ball diary|date=1 October 2001|publisher=SteveBall.com|ref=harv|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Ball\" >{{Cite book|url=http://www.steveball.com/words/presskit/#history|first=Steve|last=Ball|chapter=Steve&nbsp;Ball extended history: Side note|title=Steve&nbsp;Ball Roadshow: Extended press-kit|publisher=SteveBall.com|ref=harv|date=21 May 2009|accessdate=28 February 2012}}\n</ref> Ball's design is also used as the [[logo]] of [[Discipline Global Mobile]], the music label founded by Fripp, which has become the label for King Crimson, Fripp, and associated artists.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0000196148 |title=Discipline - King Crimson &#124; AllMusic |first=G. |last=Prato |work=allmusic.com |year= |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev2Score = B<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=king+crimson |title=Robert Christgau: CG: king crimson |first=R. |last=Christgau |work=robertchristgau.com |year=2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/kingcrimson/albums/album/140727/review/5945614/discipline |title=King Crimson: Discipline &#91;Caroline Bonus Track&#93; : Music Reviews : Rolling Stone |first=John |last=Piccarella |work=web.archive.org |year=2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502194140/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/kingcrimson/albums/album/140727/review/5945614/discipline |archivedate=2 May 2008 }}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Trouser Press]]''\n| rev4score = favourable<ref name=\"TP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=king_crimson |title=TrouserPress.com :: King Crimson |last1=Grant |first1=Steven |last2=Fleischmann |first2=Mark |last3=Robbins |first3=Ira |website=[[Trouser Press|TrouserPress.com]] |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Discipline'' reached number 41 in the [[UK Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/21481/king-crimson/ |title=King Crimson <nowiki>| Full Official Chart History |</nowiki> Official Charts Company |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> and received mixed to positive reviews. John Piccarella's review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' praised the talent and artistry of the four musicians of King Crimson, particularly Belew and Fripp's \"visionary approach to guitar playing\", but criticized the \"arty content\" of the album itself, concluding \"Here's hoping that, unlike every other King Crimson lineup, this band of virtuosos stays together long enough to transform all of their experiments into innovations.\"<ref name=\"Stone\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] described the album as \"not bad--[[Talking Heads|the Heads]] meet [[The League of Gentlemen (band)|the League of Gentlemen]].\"<ref name=\"Christgau\"/>\n\nGreg Prato's retrospective review in [[AllMusic]] gave his approval of the album, particularly applauding the unexpectedly successful combinations of Fripp and Belew's disparate playing styles. According to him, \"the pairing of these two originals worked out magically.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n[[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] ranked it at number 56 in their list of the \"Top 100 Albums of the 1980s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5882-top-100-albums-of-the-1980s/5/|title=Top 100 Albums of the 1980s|website=Pitchfork.com|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Adrian Belew]], [[Bill Bruford]], [[Robert Fripp]] and [[Tony Levin]].\n{{tracklist\n| headline   = Side A\n| title1     = Elephant Talk\n| length1    = 4:43\n| title2     = Frame by Frame\n| length2    = 5:09\n| title3     = [[Matte Kudasai]]\n| note3      = {{Nihongo2|\u5f85\u3063\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044}}, Please Wait\n| length3    = 3:47\n| title4     = [[Indiscipline]]\n| length4    = 4:33\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline   = Side B\n| title5     = [[Thela Hun Ginjeet]]\n| length5    = 6:26\n| title6     = The Sheltering Sky\n| note6      = [[Instrumental]]\n| length6    = 8:22\n| title7     = [[Discipline (instrumental)|Discipline]]\n| note7      = [[instrumental]]\n| length7    = 5:13\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline  = 30th Anniversary Series bonus track\n| collapsed = yes\n| title8    = Matte Kudasai\n| note8     = {{Nihongo2|\u5f85\u3063\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044}}, Please Wait) (Alternative version\n| length8   = 3:50\n}}\n=== 2011 40th Anniversary edition ===\n{{Track listing\n| headline    = Disc one - CD - Original Album 2011 Stereo Mix - bonus tracks\n| collapsed   = yes\n| title1      = Elephant Talk\n| writer1     = \n| length1     = 4:43\n| note1       = 2011 Stereo Mix\n| title2      = Frame by Frame\n| writer2     = \n| length2     = 5:09\n| note2       = 2011 Stereo Mix\n| title3      = [[Matte Kudasai]]\n| writer3     = \n| length3     = 3:47\n| note3       = 2011 Stereo Mix - {{Nihongo2|\u5f85\u3063\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044}}, Please Wait\n| title4      = [[Indiscipline]]\n| writer4     = \n| length4     = 4:33\n| note4       = 2011 Stereo Mix\n| title5      = [[Thela Hun Ginjeet]]\n| writer5     = \n| length5     = 6:26\n| note5       = 2011 Stereo Mix\n| title6      = The Sheltering Sky\n| writer6     = \n| length6     = 8:22\n| note6       = 2011 Stereo Mix - [[Instrumental]]\n| title7      = [[Discipline (instrumental)|Discipline]]\n| writer7     = \n| length7    